                <head>321. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>A luncheon was held at the British Embassy at 1 p.m. on October 24. It was
                    attended, on the American side, by Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                        >Dulles</persName>; <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">Christian A.
                        Herter</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_MLT1">Livingston T.
                        Merchant</persName>, Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_WJH1"
                        >Whitney</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_ECB1">C. Burke
                        Elbrick</persName>. The British participants were Prime Minister <persName
                        corresp="#p_MH1">Macmillan</persName>, Foreign Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_LSJSB1">Lloyd</persName>, Sir <persName>Norman Brook</persName>,
                    Sir <persName corresp="#p_CSHA1">Harold Caccia</persName>, Sir <persName
                        corresp="#p_DSPJ1">Pierson Dixon</persName>, Sir <persName corresp="#p_HWG1"
                        >William Hayter</persName>, and <persName>Frederick</persName> A. Bishop.
                    (Eisenhower Library, Secretary’s Appointment Book)</p>
            </div>
        </body>
